h3. Cause
This is generated from a template that is built into the JIRA OnDemand Repository Manager Plugin {{jira-ondemand-project/jira-ondemand-plugins/jira-ondemand-repository-manager-plugin/src/main/resources/templates/pre-commit.tmpl}}

Currently it checks directly in the database:
{code}
    count=$(/usr/bin/psql -tAc "select count(*) from jiraissue where pkey='$key'")
{code}

This causes the svn hook to fail since the pkey column is no longer populated.

I would expect this to fix it:
{code}
    projkey="${key%-*}"
    issuenum="${key##*-}"
    count=$(/usr/bin/psql -tAc "select count(*) FROM project p JOIN jiraissue ji ON p.id=ji.project WHERE p.pkey='$projkey' AND ji.issuenum=$issuenum")
{code}

h3. Workaround
If any customers have this issue, please raise a support request in the OnDemand Support project on [support.atlassian.com|https://support.atlassian.com] and we can manually fix it for you.

Customers migrating from Fisheye OnDemand to Fisheye Standalone are losing the functionality of referencing Fisheye changesets in JIRA comments. Those changesets references (such as *r1234*) are not being rendered as links to the actual changeset in Fisheye.

This  works when JIRA OnDemand is integrated with Fisheye OnDemand, but it's lost after Fisheye is migrated to it's standalone counterpart and linked with JIRA OnDemand.

Any text that has the revision number format *r1234* will not be rendered in JIRA, even if the instance never had Fisheye to begin with. Any string of this format will be invisible.

This lack of functionality is not being informed to customers in any of the migration documents. 

JIRA Standalone users can use the [Application Links Link Rendering Plugin|https://marketplace.atlassian.com/plugins/com.atlassian.linkers.applinks-linkers] to achieve this functionality, but this plugin is not available in OnDemand.

h3. Workaround
Users can still use monospace formatting and the text displayed as {{r211144}}

To achieve this please enter the revision as:

{noformat}
{{r211144}}
{noformat} 

As a clarification, this only affects words that match exactly:

{noformat}
r[0-9]+
{noformat}
For example, myr211144 or rev211144 will render correctly.

